In the grand, often tedious, theater of [mathematics](/Mathematics), a **ring** is an [algebraic structure](/Algebraic_structure) built from a set and two [binary operations](/Binary_operation). We call these operations addition and multiplication out of a sense of misplaced nostalgia for when numbers were simple. They behave a lot like the [addition](/Addition) and [multiplication](/Multiplication) you learned as a child, with one soul-crushing exception: multiplication doesn't have to be [commutative](/Commutative). The [elements](/Element_(mathematics)) of a ring can be familiar things like integers or [complex numbers](/Complex_number), but they can also be far more irritating objects like [polynomials](/Polynomial), [square matrices](/Square_matrices), [functions](/Function_(mathematics)), and [power series](/Power_series). Basically, it's a generalization that complicates things just enough to be useful.

